# 👅 Gustation

> The gustatory system detects **dissolved chemical stimuli (tastants) via specialized taste receptor cells (TRCs) clustered in taste buds**, signaling five primary taste qualities — sweet, salty, sour, bitter, and umami — via three cranial nerves to the nucleus tractus solitarius, and ultimately to the insular cortex. Taste is distinct from **flavor**, which integrates gustatory, olfactory (retronasal), tactile, thermal, and nociceptive signals to create the rich perception of food.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Olfaction]] — retronasal olfaction dominates flavor perception; combined in orbitofrontal cortex
- [[Cranial Nerves]] — CN VII (chorda tympani), CN IX (glossopharyngeal), CN X (vagus)
- [[Brainstem]] — nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS, medulla) as first central relay
- [[Thalamus]] — VPM nucleus relay to gustatory cortex
- [[Cerebral Cortex]] — anterior insula/frontal operculum (primary), orbitofrontal (secondary)
- [[Limbic System]] — amygdala (aversion/reward), hypothalamus (feeding regulation)

## 🗂️ Key Information
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Stimulus | Dissolved chemical tastants (must dissolve in saliva to access TRCs) |
| Receptor cells | Taste receptor cells (TRCs) — secondary sensory cells (not neurons), ~50–100 per taste bud |
| Primary afferent neurons | Geniculate ganglion (CN VII), petrosal ganglion (CN IX), nodose ganglion (CN X) |
| First central relay | Nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS), rostral gustatory nucleus, medulla |
| Thalamic relay | Ventral posteromedial nucleus (VPM), medial division (parvocellular) |
| Primary cortex | Anterior insula and frontal operculum (Brodmann areas 43, anterior 13) |
| Secondary cortex | Orbitofrontal cortex (OFC) — flavor integration with olfaction |
| Turnover | TRCs replaced every ~10–14 days |

