## 🔑 Taste Buds: Structure and Distribution

### Lingual Papillae

| Papilla Type | Location | CN Innervation | Number | Taste Buds per Papilla | Notes |
|-------------|----------|---------------|--------|----------------------|-------|
| **Fungiform** | Anterior 2/3 of tongue, scattered | CN VII (chorda tympani) | ~200–400 | 1–5 | Mushroom-shaped, visible as red dots; also contain thermoreceptors and mechanoreceptors |
| **Circumvallate (vallate)** | Posterior tongue, forms V-shaped row (sulcus terminalis) | CN IX (glossopharyngeal) | 8–12 large papillae | 100–300 | Surrounded by a moat; Ebner's (serous) glands flush moat to refresh odorant/tastant access; highest density of bitter TRCs |
| **Foliate** | Lateral margins of posterior tongue | CN IX (glossopharyngeal) | Variable folds | Many per fold | Well-developed in children, often atrophied in adults; may be mistaken for pathology when enlarged |
| **Filiform** | Entire dorsal tongue surface | None (CN V general sensation only) | Most numerous | **Zero** (no taste buds) | Mechanical; responsible for tongue texture (cat-rough surface); do NOT contain taste buds |

### Extra-Lingual Taste Buds

Taste buds also exist outside the tongue proper:

| Location | Cranial Nerve | Notes |
|----------|--------------|-------|
| Soft palate | CN VII (greater petrosal branch via palatine nerves) | Detects taste of food at back of mouth |
| Epiglottis and larynx | CN X (superior laryngeal branch, internal branch) | May mediate airway protection reflexes |
| Upper esophagus | CN X | Vestigial; may modulate swallowing |
| Pharynx | CN IX | Complements tongue input |

### Taste Bud Cellular Architecture

Each taste bud contains ~50–100 cells arranged like a garlic bulb:

| Cell Type | Morphology | Function | Taste Quality |
|-----------|-----------|---------|--------------|
| **Type I (dark cells)** | Glial-like, slender; express NTPDase2 (ATP-degrading) | Support; K⁺ and neurotransmitter clearance; salt detection (partially) | Salty (ENaC) |
| **Type II (receptor cells)** | Round; express T1R and T2R GPCRs; no conventional synapse (hemichannel ATP release) | Detect sweet, bitter, umami via GPCRs | Sweet, Bitter, Umami |
| **Type III (presynaptic cells)** | Elongated; form true synapses with afferent fibers; express SNAP25, synaptotagmin | Sour transduction (OTOP1); integrate signals; release serotonin + norepinephrine | Sour (primary) |
| **Basal cells** | Undifferentiated progenitors at base | Stem cells → replace TRCs every ~10–14 days | — |

> **TRC turnover**: unlike photoreceptors and hair cells (no regeneration), TRCs are continuously replaced, making taste relatively resilient. This explains why taste typically recovers after chemotherapy (whereas high-dose radiation to head/neck can permanently damage taste buds and salivary glands).

