## 🔑 The Five Basic Tastes: Transduction Mechanisms

| Taste | Stimulus | TRC Type | Transduction Mechanism | Receptor/Channel |
|-------|----------|----------|----------------------|-----------------|
| **Salty** | Na⁺ (and Li⁺) ions in food | Type I | Na⁺ enters apical **ENaC** (epithelial sodium channel) → direct depolarization | ENaC; **amiloride-sensitive** component = pure salt taste; amiloride-insensitive component (anion-dependent) carries harshness/irritation quality |
| **Sour** | H⁺ ions (acidity) | Type III | Protons enter via **OTOP1** (otopetrin-1, a proton-selective channel, 2019 discovery) → depolarization; H⁺ also blocks K⁺ channels; intracellular acidification activates K2P channels | OTOP1 (proton channel); also: inhibition of TASK-1/TASK-2 K⁺ channels by external H⁺ |
| **Sweet** | Sugars (glucose, fructose, sucrose), artificial sweeteners, some amino acids | Type II | **T1R2 + T1R3** heterodimer GPCR → **Gαgustducin** → ↑adenylyl cyclase → ↑cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates/closes K⁺ channel; also PLC-β2 → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release from ER → TRPM5 channel → depolarization → ATP release via pannexin-1/CALHM1 hemichannels | T1R2+T1R3 (class C GPCR); TRPM5; CALHM1 ATP hemichannel |
| **Bitter** | Toxic compounds, alkaloids, phenols, quinine, denatonium; also many medications | Type II | **T2R family** (~25 genes, broadly tuned to detect many toxins) → **Gαgustducin** → PLC-β2 → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release → TRPM5 → depolarization → ATP hemichannel release | T2R1–T2R38 and others; same downstream as sweet but different GPCR |
| **Umami** | L-glutamate (MSG), aspartate, 5'-nucleotides (IMP, GMP synergize) | Type II | **T1R1 + T1R3** heterodimer GPCR → Gαgustducin → same pathway as sweet | T1R1+T1R3; note: T1R3 is **shared** with sweet receptor (T1R2+T1R3 vs T1R1+T1R3) |

### Common Downstream Path for Sweet/Bitter/Umami (Type II cells)

1. GPCR activation → Gαgustducin + Gβγ
2. Gβγ → activates **PLC-β2** → cleaves PIP₂ → IP₃ + DAG
3. IP₃ → **IP₃R** on ER → **Ca²⁺ release** from intracellular stores
4. ↑Ca²⁺ → opens **TRPM5** (transient receptor potential melastatin 5) → Na⁺ influx → **depolarization**
5. Depolarization → **CALHM1 hemichannels** (and pannexin-1) open → **ATP release** (paracrine neurotransmitter)
6. ATP → P2X2/P2X3 receptors on afferent nerve terminals → afferent firing
7. ATP also acts on adjacent Type III cells and activates serotonin release

> **Note**: Type II TRCs do NOT form classical synapses — they release ATP via voltage-gated CALHM1 ion channels (hemichannels). This is unique in sensory biology.

