## 🔑 Gustatory Innervation (Nerve Supply)

### Three Cranial Nerves Carrying Taste

| Region | Taste Nerve | General Sensation | Ganglion (taste) | Pathway |
|--------|------------|------------------|-----------------|--------|
| **Anterior 2/3 tongue** | CN VII via **chorda tympani** (exits stylomastoid foramen, travels through middle ear, joins lingual nerve CN V3 at infratemporal fossa, exits via petrotympanic fissure) | Lingual nerve (CN V3) | **Geniculate ganglion** | Chorda tympani → CN VII proper → NTS |
| **Posterior 1/3 tongue + circumvallate papillae** | **CN IX** (glossopharyngeal nerve, lingual branches) | CN IX (also lingual branches) | **Petrosal (inferior) ganglion** | CN IX → NTS |
| **Soft palate** | CN VII via greater petrosal nerve → pterygopalatine ganglion → palatine nerves | CN V2 (palatine) | Geniculate ganglion | Greater petrosal → NTS |
| **Epiglottis, laryngopharynx** | **CN X** (vagus, internal branch of superior laryngeal nerve) | CN X (same) | **Nodose (inferior) ganglion** | CN X → NTS |

> **Clinical landmark**: The chorda tympani travels through the **middle ear** (between malleus and incus) before exiting via the petrotympanic fissure. Middle ear disease (otitis media, cholesteatoma) or surgery can damage it → **ipsilateral taste loss, anterior 2/3 tongue** + metallic taste (dysgeusia).

