## 🔑 Flavor: Integration of Multiple Senses

> "Taste is what we detect with the tongue; **flavor is what we perceive in the brain**" — flavor integrates gustatory, olfactory, tactile, thermal, and nociceptive signals primarily in the **orbitofrontal cortex**.

| Sensory Component | Contribution to Flavor | Key Receptor/System |
|------------------|----------------------|--------------------| 
| **Taste (gustation)** | Basic quality (sweet, salty, sour, bitter, umami) | Taste receptors; TRCs; CN VII/IX/X |
| **Retronasal olfaction** | **Dominant component of flavor** (~80% of "taste" is actually smell); volatile odorants travel retronasally from pharynx to olfactory epithelium during eating and swallowing | CN I; olfactory system |
| **Texture / oral somatosensation** | Mouthfeel (creaminess, crunchiness, carbonation) | CN V3 (lingual nerve); facial and pharyngeal branches |
| **Temperature** | Hot/cold modulation of flavor (warmth enhances sweetness, etc.) | TRPV1 (heat >43°C, capsaicin), TRPM8 (cool <25°C, menthol) — free nerve endings; CN V3 |
| **Chemical irritation (spice)** | Burning quality of chili (capsaicin → TRPV1), mustard (TRPA1), carbonation (CO₂ → carbonic anhydrase → acid → TRPA1) | TRPV1, TRPA1 — trigeminal free nerve endings |
| **Auditory** | Crunch sound affects perceived freshness/crispness | Auditory cortex modulates orbitofrontal flavor perception |

