## 🔑 Adaptation, Thresholds, and Special Taste Properties

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| **Taste thresholds** | Bitter lowest (quinine at ~0.000008 M — evolutionary protective function detecting toxins); sweet higher (sucrose ~0.01 M); salty and sour intermediate |
| **Taste adaptation** | Prolonged exposure to same tastant → reduced perceived intensity; receptor-level (channel inactivation) and central; recovery in minutes |
| **Miracle fruit (miraculin)** | Glycoprotein from Synsepalum dulcificum; binds T1R2+T1R3 at acidic pH → activates sweet receptor → makes sour taste sweet; used in taste disturbance clinics |
| **Gymnemic acid** | Blocks T1R2+T1R3 → blocks sweetness perception; also blocks T2R binding |
| **Sodium chloride vs. MSG enhancement** | Salt enhances flavor by reducing perception of bitterness and sourness (Na⁺ suppresses these modalities) |
| **Supertasters** | ~25% of population; highest fungiform papilla density; most sensitive to bitter (especially 6-n-propylthiouracil/PROP); more T2R38 functional alleles |

