## 🏥 Clinical Significance

| Condition | Mechanism | Key Features | Notes |
|-----------|-----------|-------------|-------|
| **Ageusia** | Complete loss of taste | Rare as isolated finding; most "taste loss" = anosmia; CN VII, IX, X combined lesion needed for complete ageusia | Distinguished from anosmia by electrogustometry or direct tastant testing to tongue surface |
| **Dysgeusia** | Distorted taste | Metallic taste: **ACE inhibitors** (most common drug cause), metronidazole, carboplatin, zinc deficiency, CN VII injury; bitter: chloramphenicol | Medication review; zinc supplementation if deficient |
| **CN VII lesion — Bell's palsy / temporal bone fracture** | Above chorda tympani origin → ipsilateral anterior 2/3 tongue taste loss; above stapedius branch → + hyperacusis; above greater petrosal origin → + dry eye (lacrimal) | Lacrimation, salivation (submandibular + sublingual glands via chorda tympani), stapedius reflex, anterior 2/3 taste all lost above stylomastoid foramen level | Topographic localization of CN VII lesion via taste/reflex testing |
| **COVID-19 dysgeusia** | Multifactorial: sustentacular cell damage (olfactory) + direct taste receptor cell disruption + inflammatory cytokine effects on TRCs | Ageusia/hypogeusia + anosmia in early COVID-19 (high specificity for COVID-19 in pandemic context); usually recovers weeks-months; persistent post-COVID dysgeusia/parosmia in some | Sustentacular cell ACE2/TMPRSS2 expression; TRC ACE2 also present |
| **Burning mouth syndrome** | Poorly understood; proposed: small fiber neuropathy of CN V → central sensitization; loss of taste modulatory fibers; hormonal (post-menopausal) | Chronic burning pain/discomfort on tongue/oral mucosa, often without visible lesion; often with dysgeusia (metallic, bitter); anxiety/depression comorbidity | Diagnosis of exclusion; clonazepam (topical), alpha-lipoic acid, cognitive-behavioral therapy |
| **Gustatory aura / phantom taste** | Temporal lobe epilepsy — ictal discharge in gustatory cortex (anterior insula/operculum) or uncus | Sudden unpleasant taste (metallic, bitter, sour); aura before complex partial seizure; "uncinate fit" (Hughlings Jackson) | EEG + MRI temporal lobe; anti-epileptic drugs |
| **Radiation-induced taste loss** | Radiation to head/neck → direct damage to taste buds + salivary gland dysfunction (xerostomia → impaired tastant dissolving) | Hypogeusia beginning during treatment; partial recovery over months; xerostomia persists → ongoing taste impairment | Amifostine (radioprotectant); artificial saliva; zinc supplementation |
| **Zinc deficiency** | Zinc required for carbonic anhydrase VI (salivary; affects tastant dissolving) and normal TRC turnover | Hypogeusia/dysgeusia + anosmia; seen in malnutrition, Crohn's disease, alcoholism, medications (ACEI, thiazides) | Zinc supplementation (zinc sulfate or gluconate) |

